== Overview == In the {{ill|Kojiki|ja|古事記|12=draft}}, Ōtonoji no Kami is the elder brother, and Ōtonobe no Kami is the younger sister. In the {{ill|Nihon Shoki|ja|日本書紀|12=draft}}, they are called Ōtonomichi no Mikoto and Ōtonobe no Mikoto, respectively. The {{ill|Sendai Kuji Hongi|ja|先代旧事本紀|12=draft}} refers to them as Ōtomahiko no Mikoto and Ōtomahime no Mikoto.
They are described as the fifth generation of the {{ill|Kamiyo Nanayo|ja|神世七代|12=draft}}. Ōtonoji no Kami is a male deity, while Ōtonobe no Kami is a female deity.
The names symbolize the solidification of the earth. "Ōto" is interpreted in various ways, including as references to male and female generative organs, representing the earth’s readiness for life creation. Following these deities, Omotaru and Kashikone appear, signaling the world’s complete formation, with subsequent creation by {{ill|Izanagi|ja|伊邪那岐|12=draft}} and {{ill|Izanami|ja|伊邪那美|12=draft}}.
Ōtonoji is interpreted as "the great father at the village gate," while Ōtonobe signifies "the great woman at the village gate." These deities are believed to have been worshipped as guardians of gates in ancient settlements.
